  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is universally classified as a legally prohibited activity. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"), often through complex transactions and financial maneuvers. This activity is criminalized under laws in most countries, including China, as it undermines the integrity of financial systems, facilitates organized crime, and threatens economic and social stability.\n\nIn China, the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China** (\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u53cd\u6d17\u94b1\u6cd5) explicitly prohibits money laundering and outlines measures to prevent and combat such activities. Chinese authorities, including the People's Bank of China and the Ministry of Public Security, actively enforce these laws and collaborate internationally to combat money laundering. The Communist Party of China and the Chinese government consistently strengthen legal frameworks and regulatory oversight to safeguard financial security and social justice.",
